        "timestamp": 1721462847
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't it simpler to just assume a LinearOrder on iota? Which could be transferred via equivFin if necessary?</p>",
        "id": 452836346,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1721479186
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Antoine, I'm not quite sure if you're responding to the original or most recent message, but <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=QuadraticMap.toBilin#doc\">docs#QuadraticMap.toBilin</a> assumes a linear order, while the non-constructive <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearMap.BilinMap.toQuadraticMap_surjective#doc\">docs#LinearMap.BilinMap.toQuadraticMap_surjective</a> does not.</p>",
        "id": 452836572,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1721479365
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(those links won't become valid for a few hours)</p>",
        "id": 452836580,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1721479379
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Regarding the original question, it does seem like there should be a <code>Fintype ι → Trunc (LinearOrder ι)</code> somewhere.</p>",
        "id": 452836752,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1721479542
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But as you say, you could just make do with the equiv with <code>Fin</code> and do your work there instead</p>",
        "id": 452836832,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1721479597
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I was indeed responding to a mixture of the most recent messages, sorry.</p>",
        "id": 452863594,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1721494467
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Regarding the usefulness of some <code>Fintype ι → Trunc (LinearOrder ι)</code>, there are many instances of this kind to have (one for every abstract existence theorem), and it is probably tedious to enter them all by hand.  (Well orderings, bases, fixed points, minimal elements, etc.) What would be a sustainable design so that they are easily accessed, in a relatively standard way, without any risk of missing one.</p>",
        "id": 452863816,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1721494653
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Finite.equivFin#doc\">docs#Finite.equivFin</a> is just an invocation of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Finite.exists_equiv_fin#doc\">docs#Finite.exists_equiv_fin</a>. It would probably be nice to have them created using a  <code>@[choose]</code> tag.</p>",
        "id": 452863998,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1721494789
    }
]